# --- Virtual environments -----------------------------------------------
.venv/
venv/

# --- Local secrets ------------------------------------------------------
.env

# --- Tenant configuration -----------------------------------------------
# `config/tenant.yml` and any per-environment tenant.<env>.yml files
# carry the real Azure AAD tenant ID, subscription ID(s), resource group,
# and workspace name(s). These are not credentials, but they are
# infrastructure-reconnaissance gold and must not leak. Track ONLY the
# `.example.yml` templates. CI materialises the real file from a
# GitHub Actions secret (see `.github/actions/pipeline-setup/action.yml`).
config/tenant.yml
config/tenant.*.yml
!config/tenant.*.yml.example
!config/tenant.yml.example

# --- IDE / editor scratch -----------------------------------------------
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp

# --- Pipeline runtime + per-run output ----------------------------------
# These directories carry data the pipeline emits at run time (audit
# records, state snapshots, on-demand exports, scratch snapshots from
# `pipeline collect --path`, etc). They are NOT versioned content —
# committing them by accident is what caused the 2477-file "git add
# -A" incident on the rename-bootstrap branch. The patterns below
# eliminate that mistake class.
#
# `audit/`            — JSONL hash-chained apply records (per-day files).
# `state/`            — per-env state files (`pipeline state` writes here).
# `exports/`          — one-shot exports (`pipeline collect` archive output).
# `.snapshot/`        — scratch snapshots used by drift round-trip tests.
# `.test-export/`     — scratch dir for ad-hoc export tests.
# `drift-report.json` — output of `pipeline drift --report` written into
#                       the repo root by the workflow + local debugging.
#
# Anchored to the repo root with a leading `/` so the patterns do NOT
# shadow same-named Python subpackages. `contentops/audit/` is a real
# tracked subpackage; with an unanchored `audit/` pattern, `git add -A`
# in the public mirror sync silently stripped the whole subpackage from
# the mirror tree (it's tracked in this repo, but freshly-copied files
# in the mirror are untracked-and-ignored, so they never staged). The
# downstream consumer broke on import. Lesson: in a repo whose tree
# is reflowed by a tool that re-stages files, runtime-data gitignore
# rules MUST be anchored or named such that they can't collide with
# code paths.

/audit/
/state/
/exports/
/.snapshot/
/.test-export/
/drift-report.json
/.e2e-results.json
/alerts-reports/
# `coverage*.md/json` + `coverage-navigator.json` — ad-hoc on-demand
# output of `contentops coverage [--gaps|--d3fend|--by-source]` and
# `contentops navigator` written into the repo root for local review.
# The tracked heatmap that the workflow posts is a PR comment, not a file.
/coverage.md
/coverage.json
/coverage-*.md
/coverage-*.json

# `reports/*-findings.md` — ad-hoc security-review / findings markdown
#                        (e.g. phase1-*-findings.md). Scratch write-ups, never
#                        versioned content, and must never reach the public
#                        mirror (public-sync strips + the safety check blocks
#                        reports/*-findings.md as a backstop). The published
#                        reports/latest.md is intentionally tracked and synced.
/reports/*-findings.md

# --- KQL strict-lint wrapper build artefacts ----------------------------
# Sources live at tools/kql_strict/ and are the canonical artifact; the
# built DLL + intermediate .NET output is generated by CI (or by the
# scripts/build_kql_strict.* helpers locally) and is never committed.
# See tools/kql_strict/README.md.
/tools/kql_strict.dll
/tools/kql_strict.deps.json
/tools/kql_strict.runtimeconfig.json
/tools/kql_strict/bin/
/tools/kql_strict/obj/

# --- Claude Code / agent scratch ----------------------------------------
# Local per-user agent state — never repository content.
.claude/
